We are not going away. Our rights, our freedom, is everyone's freedom. Because first they came for the trans kids, but eventually they will come for you too. If you believe in freedom, you have to support trans rights, and the dignity if letting people discover themselves.

What I can say to the cis and pick-me's out there, is realizing/acknowledging my true nature, my identity, has been more liberating than anything else in my life. It's only a disorder if you repress and deny part of your being. Trans/nonbinary ppl have been here forever.

She was shocked, but ultimately she immediately accepted me, and within minutes she got out her makeup and we had a day of girl time, and I can't express the joy/euphoria I experienced. She is still processing, but so am I.

I've had bad bouts of dysphoria in the past, but they eventually faded, and I was able to go back repressing, but this time was different, and she would not let me protect her anymore, she wanted to breathe. So, I overcame my fear and confessed to my wife.

This began before my trip to see my son, suffering from two recent autoimmune diseases. I had reached out to a few young transwomen in DMs, which honestly didn't help me, and I felt a bit discarded/disbelieved by both. I cried through most of the flight home, alone.

I was walking down the hall at my work and I became acutely aware if how I was carefully, unconsciously, monitoring my movements to "mimic" those of a guy. I noticed I was moving more like a woman and self-corrected. My world began to crumble, and the whispers became megaphones.

I had resigned myself to being content with my repressed mind, my inner world of hidden dysphoria. But a over two months ago, maybe three at this point, the dysphoria went from tolerable to near mental breakdown. I can trace the point where it began.

I actually came out to a friend almost 30 yrs ago; it didn't go well, and I was so scared of the threat of sexual violence, I repressed and tried hard to just "be a guy," knowing my own inner thoughts, my dreams of the magic wand (the button), occasional dysphoria.

I'm genderqueer and trans. I've been open about it in replies to others, but not direct tweets. This is a recent realization, and 99.9% of ppl in my life still don't know; I'm ok with that. This post will likely go unseen, but here you go, it's official. You heard it from me.
